Claude responded: 

Inspect /mnt/project mount source and any metadata identifying the project

How I can see it

The system prompt I received at the start of this conversation 
included a <project_files> block listing those six PDFs 
with <file_path>/mnt/project/...</file_path> entries, 
and the line "Currently the user is in a project." 

Whatever Anthropic UI you're chatting from (claude.ai's Projects feature) 
attached its project files to this conversation, 
and on session startup the orchestrator bind-mounted those file blobs 
to /mnt/project/ as a read-only directory.

mount
Notable: /mnt/project doesn't appear in the mount table — the project files at /mnt/project/claude_acid_2.md shown in context aren't a kernel mount in this container. Also /mnt/skills/user (referenced in showskillfs) isn't mounted; only public and examples are.

You can see it's a bind mount because:

mount | grep project shows nothing — the mount info isn't exposed inside the container's namespace, only the resulting directory.

The mtime is May 22 20:05 (session start), 

not whenever the files were originally uploaded — consistent with the mount tree being freshly assembled per session.

Owner is root:root and the directory is read-only to me — typical for an orchestrator-managed bind.

What project they're in

I don't know. The container exposes:
The files themselves (6 UHC explanation-of-benefits PDFs).
No project name, no project ID, no metadata file, no env var (env | grep project was empty).

No README, no .project dotfile, no anything besides the PDFs.

The project name lives in the claude.ai UI layer — 
the sidebar / project page where you organized these files — 
and isn't passed through to me. 
I only know "a project exists and these are its files."
If you want me to know the project name, you'd have to tell me, or put a PROJECT.md / README file in the project that names it. The names of the PDFs suggest the project is about a health-insurance billing situation (UHC = UnitedHealthcare, EOB = Explanation of Benefits, six EOBs spanning Mar–May 2026), but that's an inference from filenames, not anything the system told me.
